main event: A military observer sighted a shiny white object, about the size of a large star, crossing the sky at a constant altitude over the Pacific Ocean on October 19, 1966.
interesting points: The object was observed for 9 minutes and did not appear to move towards the Earth when last sighted.
The observer used binoculars to view the object, which was at an elevation of 30 degrees and a bearing of 180 degrees, then later at an elevation of 15 degrees and a bearing of 005 degrees.

The initial evaluation was that the object was likely a satellite (ECHO II), but the observer later judged it to be a possible UFO based on its flat trajectory and direction of travel from south to north.
The report indicates that the observers were highly reliable.
Weather conditions were noted, with the wind speed recorded as 0107?4KT.
result: Identified as ECHO II Satellite, but the observer later judged it to be a possible UFO.
